    <title>Combined summary - (no subject)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T17:59:49.655850+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-May/002659.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers recently engaged in email conversations that covered various topics related to Bitcoin's upgrades and maintenance. One topic of discussion was the need to separate "rule change" fixes and "bug fix" releases for Bitcoin. Melvin Carvalho suggested this approach, while Luke-Jr pointed out that clients with different rules cannot run on the same blockchain/network.Another topic that arose was the flexible transactions (FT) feature in Bitcoin. Tom Zander responded to criticisms by Matt Corallo, stating that FT is safer because it changes fewer concepts than SegWit, which has been met with objections by some wallets who are adopting a "wait and see" approach. A discussion on soft-fork security provided more detail on upgrades required.In addition, the necessity of rule changes for Bitcoin to evolve was discussed. Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn engaged in this discussion and suggested the best venue for suggesting rule changes. It was recognized that some rule changes may be necessary in the future, but they should be carefully considered before being implemented.However, the current codebase of Bitcoin Classic was criticized for blatant security holes, including out-of-bound memory accesses in its 80-LoC deserialize method. Thus, it was agreed that non-technical changes are needed as well.Overall, the email conversations highlighted the importance of careful consideration when implementing changes to Bitcoin's codebase, especially in terms of rule changes and security measures.</summary>
